Begins Monday, August 31 (Monday & Thursday Pickup)
Grab & Go Meals are available for pick up from Vista Grande High School, Casa Grande Union High School, and the District Office locations. The service times are 6:30-7:45 a.m. then again 10:30-11:30 a.m. [MONDAY] Meals for Monday, Tuesday, and Wednesday are picked up. [THURSDAY] Meals for Thursday and Friday are picked up. Breakfast and Lunch are served at the same time. These pickup times will be modified when in-person instruction begins. A document such as a copy of the student's class schedule with the student name, ID#, and which school they attend or last year's Student ID (2019/20) is required for each meal pick up and accountability. Breakfast prices are Free, Reduced-Price (30 cents), or Full-Price ($2.00). Lunch prices are Free, Reduced-Price (40 cents), or Full-Price ($3.00). If a student has a paid or reduced-price lunch status, their lunch account will be charged. Students are responsible for negative balances.Visit www.cguhsd.org/doFoodServices.aspx.

post_text:
Rotary Student of the Month
Evan Chaparro, son of Tandy and Alex Chaparro, was recognized by Principal Glenda Cole on Tuesday, September 1, as September’s VGHS Rotary Student of the Month. As a senior, he has accumulated a list of activities and accomplishments. Activities include: Student Council (3-Yr President), Key Club (1-Yr President), Robotics, Math League, AP Math Club, AP Stats Club, National Honor Society, Casa Grande Youth Commission, UArizona KEYS Intern, and ASU SCENE Intern. His personal accomplishments include earning straight A’s all four years (4.740 GPA), being ranked number one in the Senior Class, and earning the Vista Grande Academic Award all four years of high school. In the future, he wants to attend the University of Southern California, major in Chemical Engineering, use his career to help solve some of the problems we face today, and make a name for himself both in his career and in life.

post_text: School-wide Positive Behavioral Interventions and Supports (PBIS) is a system of tools and strategies for defining, teaching, acknowledging appropriate behavior, and correcting inappropriate behavior. It is a framework for creating customized school systems that supports student outcomes and academic success. PBIS is for the whole school, it is preventative, and it changes the paradigm of focus from negative behaviors and exchanges to positive expectations and interactions. Positive Behavioral Interventions and Supports (PBIS) is nationally recognized and implemented in over 22,000 schools in all 50 states. Vista Grande High School PBIS is coordinated by Behavioral Interventionist Jared Walther. Visit www.cguhsd.org/vgPBIS.aspx.

Begins Monday, August 31 (Monday & Thursday Pickup)
Grab & Go Meals are available for pick up from Vista Grande High School, Casa Grande Union High School, and the District Office locations. The service times are 6:30-7:45 a.m. then again 10:30-11:30 a.m. [MONDAY] Meals for Monday, Tuesday, and Wednesday are picked up. [THURSDAY] Meals for Thursday and Friday are picked up. Breakfast and Lunch are served at the same time. These pickup times will be modified when in-person instruction begins. A document such as a copy of the student's class schedule with the student name, ID#, and which school they attend or last year's Student ID (2019/20) is required for each meal pick up and accountability. Breakfast prices are Free, Reduced-Price (30 cents), or Full-Price ($2.00). Lunch prices are Free, Reduced-Price (40 cents), or Full-Price ($3.00). If a student has a paid or reduced-price lunch status, their lunch account will be charged. Students are responsible for negative balances.Visit www.cguhsd.org/doFoodServices.aspx.

post_text: Emilio Barreras (VGHS Junior) verbally committed to play college baseball at Cal State Fullerton earlier this week. Cal State Fullerton is a nationally ranked program year-in and year-out. They have had many student-athletes come through their program and make the big leagues. Their program has also won multiple NCAA Division I National Titles. Cal State Fullerton is one of the elite flagship programs amongst all of NCAA Division I baseball. VGHS Spartan Baseball is coached by PE/Health Teacher Harley Grigg. post_text:
Free & Reduced-Price Meal Application
Casa Grande Union High School District will participate in the National School Lunch Program and the School Breakfast Program. As part of this program, Casa Grande Union High School and Vista Grande High School will offer healthy meals every school day. Breakfast costs $2.00; Lunch costs $3.00. Reduced-Price meals cost $0.30 for Breakfast and $0.40 for Lunch. To apply for free or reduced-price meals, complete an application and return it to the school unless the household has already received notification that their children are approved for free meals this year. Application forms were distributed to all households with a letter informing households of the availability of free and reduced-price meals for their children and what is required to complete the application. Applications may also be completed online at www.cguhsd.org/doFoodServices.aspx and are also available at your school’s Front Office and Food Service Department. For more information, contact Carla Wells at (520) 876-9400 ext. 4146 or cwells@cguhsd.org.

Certificate of Excellence in Financial Reporting Award
The Gold Standard in Comprehensive Annual Financial Reports

For more than 45 years, the Certificate of Excellence in Financial Reporting (COE) has honored school districts for their high-quality Comprehensive Annual Financial Reports (CAFRs). Casa Grande Union High School District #82 Business Services was recently honored with the award. A CAFR includes information that goes beyond the minimums established by the National Council on Governmental Accounting (NCGA). Transparency and quality financial information are critical in today’s education environment. CGUHSD Business Services Department is led by Gina Salazar, Business Services Director, and Sharon Rodriguez, Business Services Manager. Visit www.cguhsd.org/BusinessServices.aspx.

post_text: Every 10 years, the census counts every person living in the United States. This includes newborns, children, grandparents, friends, and anyone who is living or staying in your home. When you respond to the census, please count everyone so Arizona gets its share of funding. The $675 billion in annual funds allocated to states is based on population and used for schools, school lunch programs, playgrounds, after-school programs, health clinics, public transportation, roads, community senior centers, and other vital programs. The census is our opportunity to shape the next ten years in Arizona. Complete the census at https://my2020census.gov/.

Your responses are being shared with our task force planning committees to be included in the planning process. A comprehensive plan for reopening schools will be presented to our Governing Board in our Tuesday, July 7, meeting. In the meantime, we
would like to inform our community of some key measures we are already taking and ones we are currently reviewing:
http://www.cguhsd.org/downloads/CGUHSD-ReopeningParentCommunicationUpdated-Current.pdf

In an effort to beat the heat and still serve the students in our community, some adjustments to our food service days and times have been made. Effective Wednesday, June 10, meals will be distributed three days a week: Monday, Wednesday, and Friday. While the number of days has decreased, children (ages 18 years and younger) still receive meals for all seven (7) days. Monday’s provided meals are for Monday and Tuesday; Wednesday’s provided meals are for Wednesday and Thursday; and Friday’s provided meals are for Friday through Sunday. For menu information, visit www.cguhsd.org/doCOVID19MealService.aspx.

post_text: Congratulations to Karina Avalos who earned 2nd Place in the 2020 AZ-01 Congressional Art Competition. Her artwork, The Dancing Fan, will be displayed for one year at the U.S. Capitol. Each spring, the Congressional Institute sponsors a nationwide high school visual art competition to recognize and encourage artistic talent in the nation and in each congressional district. Students submit entries to their representative’s office, and panels of district artists select the winning entries. Winners are recognized both in their district and at an annual awards ceremony in Washington, D.C. VGHS art classes are taught by taught by Fine Arts & CTE Teacher Carlos Jimenez. Visit http://www.cguhsd.org/cjimenezFineArts.aspx.

post_text: CGUHS Seniors must attend Senior Check Out Day where they will return CGUHS property, pay outstanding fees & fines, and receive their diploma. Collect and return CGUHS property such as laptop, charger, textbooks, calculator, library items, uniforms, and equipment. Review your student bookstore account. Check your emails for outstanding fees & fines such as cafeteria balance, Student ID replacement, unreturned uniforms, AP exam, etc. Yearbooks will also be available for both pick-up and purchase (limited supply available). If you have not already paid for a yearbook, you can purchase one online. To help stop the spread of Covid-19, we are asking that you please arrive during your designated day and time, and that you practice appropriate safety measures such as following physical distancing guidelines, wear a mask, and only attend if you are feeling healthy. Seniors are divided alphabetically according to last name. Please enter CGUHS at the gate from the student parking lot and proceed to our IT Room J102 for your first stop. To assist with check-out, please bring your Student ID.

post_text: VGHS Seniors must attend Senior Check Out Day where they will return VGHS property, pay outstanding fees & fines, and receive their diploma. Collect and return VGHS property such as laptop, charger, textbooks, calculator, library items, uniforms, and equipment. Review your student bookstore account. Check your emails for outstanding fees & fines such as cafeteria balance, Student ID replacement, unreturned uniforms, AP exam, etc. Bring cash to pay. Yearbooks will not be for sale during this time. Arrive on your designated day and time. Seniors are divided alphabetically according to last name (see below). Enter VGHS at the gate by the Football Field (Marquis Gate). Security will direct you to a designated area in the Student Parking Lot. Patiently wait in your car until a VGHS staff member releases the student to enter the Small Gym. Students will wear their Student ID, mask, and gloves. VGHS Senior Check Out Day Video may be found at https://youtu.be/VmtiW4NsZbw.

As of Monday, June 1, the District Office, CGUHS, and VGHS are reopening for employees to return to work. We will follow all federal, state, and local social distancing guidelines. For the safety and well-being of the employees who work in our offices, the offices will remain closed to outside visitors without a previously scheduled appointment. If you should need to meet in-person with anyone who works in one of our offices, please call in advance and schedule an appointment with them before coming to an office. Staff are available by phone and email, and will respond regularly during our summer office hours, Monday-Thursday. Visit our individual websites for specific contact/directory information:

VGHS | www.cguhsd.org/vgDirectory.aspx

post_text: VGHS’s SkillsUSA Technical Theater was recognized with a Gold Level Chapter of Distinction award. Gold Level is the highest level a chapter can receive. For a chapter to be selected, students must file a lengthy application with various levels and complete numerous tasks and activities designed around developing personal, professional, and technical skills. The Spartans are advised by CTE & Fine Arts Teacher KJ Harding. Visit www.cguhsd.org/vgSkillsUSA.aspx.

post_text: Congratulations to one of our outstanding Economics Teachers, Beth Craig, for being named EconHero by The Thomas R. Brown Foundation in April 2020. The Brown Foundations seek to advance the use of economic principles in public and private decision making through strategic partnerships and educational programs. The program goal is to equip teachers to increase student exposure to fundamental principles of economics in a neutral and nonpartisan way, and to help students develop an appreciation of how economic analysis applies to everyday choices as well as business and policy issues. For more information, visit www.brownfoundations.com/economics-for-teachers and www.cguhsd.org/bcraig.aspx.

post_text: CGUHS’s Santiago Hernandez was recognized by CTE Teacher George Courtney as the CTE Automotive Technology Student of the Year on May 5. Santiago has been in the Automotive Program for three (3) years. During his time in the program, he has attained two (2) Automotive Service Excellence certifications in Brakes and Light Maintenance and Repair. He also competed in SkillsUSA competitions. Mr. Courtney stated, “Santiago is one of my students who has helped build a new identity and culture for the program. I am confident Santiago will be successful in his future endeavors. He has been accepted into Universal Technical Institute where he will attend this fall. For his hard work and commitment, we will honor him with a starter tool set from Matco Tools valued at $1500.” Visit www.cguhsd.org/gcourtney.aspx.

post_text: Mark Cruz has been accepted into the Barrett Summer Scholars program through Arizona State University. The Barrett Summer Scholars program provides students with the opportunity to experience college firsthand and prepare for enrollment and success at Arizona State University (ASU) and Barrett, the ASU Honors College. The program is designed for academically talented and motivated students entering the 8th, 9th, and 10th grade. Mark will complete college-level course work and participate in a community of peers from across the state. Due to COVID-19, the courses will be virtual this year.

post_text: Pandemic EBT(P-EBT), as introduced in H.R. 6201, the Families First Coronavirus Response Act, provides assistance to households with children who are eligible for free or reduced-price school meals while schools are out of session due to the COVID-19 pandemic. The Arizona P-EBT Pandemic School Meal Replacement Benefits program is a partnership between the Department of Economic Security (DES), Arizona Department of Education (ADE), and USDA Food and Nutrition Service. Visit https://des.az.gov/services/basic-needs/food-assistance/arizona-p-ebt-pandemic-school-meal-replacement-benefits.

post_text: CGUHS’s Career & Technical Education (CTE) Teacher Casey Farnsworth received the Arizona Agriculture Teachers Association’s (AATA) South Central District Teacher of the Year Award. The purpose of the award is to recognize members and supporters for their contributions to the improvement of Agricultural Education. The AATA Selection Committee includes Agriculture teachers, University of Arizona staff, and Arizona Department of Education staff who utilize a selection process based on the following factors: program & community description, teaching philosophy, curriculum & instruction examples, experiential learning, membership in professional organizations, partnerships & marketing, program & professional improvement, completion of state forms & supporting materials, and letters of recommendation from administrators. Mr. Farnsworth is now in the running for the AATA Teacher of the Year which will take place at the 45th Annual Arizona Career and Technical Education Summer Conference in July. Visit www.cguhsd.org/cfarnsworth.aspx.

Rotary Student of the Month
Brynna McQuillen is a senior at Vista Grande High School and the daughter of Stacy and Richie McQuillen. Her activities and accomplishments include Track & Field, Cross Country, Co-Founder and Co-President of Spartans Athletic Advisory Committee, hosting a Peanut Butter Drive that collected over 600 jars, finishing 4th Place at the 2018 and 2019 Cross Country State Championships, and was the 1600 Meter Runner-Up at the 2019 State Track Championships and 4th Place in the 3200 Meter and 800 Meter. Her personal activities and accomplishments include 2019 May Fox Sports AZ Student Athlete of the Month, volunteering at Banner Casa Grande Medical Center for three years, and completing over 300 hours of community service. Her life and career goals are to attend Kansas State University and major in Psychology, and possibly becoming a Sports Psychologist. She plans to run Cross Country and Outdoor/Indoor Track at K-State.

post_text:
Rotary Student of the Month
Adriana Gonzalez-Chavez is a senior at Casa Grande Union High School and daughter of Elizabeth Chavez. Her activities and accomplishments include being a member of Cross Country, Track, National Honor Society, National Technical Honor Society, Key Club, Academic and Straight A Honor Roll award recipient, and is enrolled in the Dental Assisting Program at CAVIT. Her personal activities and accomplishments include completing over 150 hours of volunteer work during her high school years, cleaning local roads, exercising animals at the Valley Humane Society, fundraising for school clubs, assisting with school events, and helping a community member move from their home with ease. Her life and career goals are to attend ASU’s Walter Cronkite School of Journalism and Mass Communication and become a journalist so she can bring more national support and recognition for families of a single parent like her own. She also wants to be a role model for children of single-parent families.

post_text: Congratulations to CGUHS senior Brady Stephens for receiving the ASU Medallion Scholarship Award which includes a $3,600 renewable annual scholarship. The Medallion Scholarship Program is a comprehensive program that recognizes and develops a proud tradition of leadership, scholarship, and service. The Alumni Association’s Medallion Scholarship Program Selection Committee selects 35 Medallion Scholars for each year’s entering freshman class by reviewing applications and interviewing the scholars.

post_text:
Students in SEI Reading, Oral English Conversation, and Vocabulary have been working on acrostic poems. An acrostic poem is a poem where certain letters in each line spell out a word or phrase. Typically, the first letters of each line are used to spell the message, but they can appear anywhere. The Cougars are taught by English & ELD Teacher Bobbi Devet. Visit www.cguhsd.org/bdevetSEIReadingOralEngConvVocab.aspx.

Acrostic Poem
by Luigi Magallanez Perez

L-LEADER, a quiet achiever
U-UNDERSTANDING, simply the best
I-INVENTIVE, always full of surprises
G-GENEROUS, a kind heart
I-INQUISITIVE, a curious mind

post_text: CGUHS Students took part in this annual event that showcased their academic and performance skills and talents. It highlighted their proficiency in Science, Technology, Engineering, Arts, and Mathematics through a visual and hands-on display and confident presentation of projects and output. The annual festival entertained and amazed the audience through an array of presentations performed by talented students from the Dance Group, Color Guard, and the Blue Notes. This year’s SciTech Festival was sponsored by the STEM Advisory Council headed by Julia Leija and volunteers from the AzHOSA CGUHS Chapter, Engineering, Key Club, and the National Honors Society. The STEM Advisory Council is advised by CTE & Science Teacher Noel Que. Visit www.cguhsd.org/cgSTEMAdvisoryCouncil.aspx.

post_text: Students from the VGHS Graphic Design program had lunch with Southwest Gas staff and presented their Valley Division logo designs on Monday, March 2. For the first time this year, these students experienced a real day in the life of a graphic designer. Not only did they work on a class assignment, but an actual job as well. Southwest Gas Corporation (SWGC) needed a logo design for their local Valley District branch, so they gave the design students this amazing opportunity. The company provided details and ideas of what they were looking for in a design, and they eagerly took on the job. Designs were original and freehand drawn using only a computer mouse - no clipart or anything taken from online. Students were invited to present their logo proposals and did a fantastic job. They were professionally dressed, enthusiastic, and delivered top-notch presentations that impressed everyone at SWGC. The students are taught by Fine Arts & CTE Teacher Carlos Jimenez. Visit www.cguhsd.org/cjimenezGraphicDesignI.aspx.

post_text: CGUHS freshman Gracie Mark has been named 3rd Place Winner in the Gila River Indian Community Mul-Chu-Tha Essay Contest. This prestigious award encompasses the review of many applications from Gila River local schools including many that lie outside of the community’s boundaries. Along with other winners from the contest, Gracie was recognized at the Mul-Chu-Tha Community Day. Her essay was displayed at the Governance Center Lobby from March 2-6 for public view. Congratulations, Gracie!

post_text: Career and Technical Education (CTE) held a CTE Career Fair at Stanfield Elementary School on Wednesday, February 26. CTE is preparing our students to become the highly skilled workforce of our community, state, and nation. Students in our CTE programs take what they learn and apply it to something relevant to real-life experiences. Growing hydroponic crops, building robots, preparing a gourmet meal, or extracting DNA are examples of the daily activities. Each CTE program within the district leads to a certification or industry credential. In addition to teaching our students the technical skills for a career, our programs instill the employability skills that will make them successful in their future occupation. We are college and career readiness. Visit www.cguhsd.org/CTE.aspx.

Visit www.cguhsd.org/vgJROTC.aspx.

post_text: Isabella Salazar is a student at Vista Grande High School and daughter of Hector and Brenda Salazar. Her activities and accomplishments include being a member of Student Council, Yearbook, Parent Teacher Student Organization (PTSO), Journalism, Travel Club, AP Club Elite Dance Company, and Varsity Cheer where she is the current captain, all while maintaining a high GPA. Her personal activities include over 400 volunteer hours at Banner Health Hospital in Casa Grande. She has also taken dance lessons at The Studio since the age of 4, taking her passion one step further by starting her own business, “Bella’s Creative Dance” and teaching ballet to students ages 3-10 through the city’s parks and recreation program. After graduation, Isabella hopes to attend the University of Arizona to obtain a Bachelor of Science in Nursing (BSN) and become a Registered Nurse (R.N.).

post_text: Logan Brown is a student at Casa Grande Union High School and the son of Scott and Angela Brown. His activities and accomplishments include being a member of Key Club, National Honor Society, Tri-M Music Honors Society, Marching Band, and Percussion Ensemble. He has maintained a 4.41 GPA for four years, been named AP Scholar with Distinction, and scored an average of 3.5 on all his AP Exams. His personal activities include marching with the Academy Drum and Bugle Corps for the summer of 2019 following a rigorous audition process which included students from all over the country. He hopes to pursue a degree in Music Education at the University of Arizona.

post_text: The CGUHS National Honor Society (NHS) sent 13 students to Washington, D.C., for five days from January 29 to February 2. Two parent chaperones and advisors Paul and Norma Machelor accompanied the students. Students participating were Nicholas Camacho, Jenna Gonzales, Amberlyn Goswick, Genevieve Hayes, Sienna Husted, Caden Mace, Maria Emilia Machelor, Alexis Mohler, Rebecca Myers, Hannah O’Neil, Alyssa Price, Andrea Ramirez, and Corbin Smith. All involved had an excellent and very rewarding experience. Highlights included museums and monuments on the Mall, learning from and interacting with NHS students from all over the country during the NHS LEAD Conference, and having a blast ice skating on the Mall. Visit the Cougars webpage at www.cguhsd.org/cgNHS.aspx.

post_text: The Casa Grande Elite Dance Company (CGEDC) had a blast at their Disney Performing Arts Tour this past week. The team took a Masterclass where they learned professional Disney Parade choreography. CGEDC also had the opportunity to experience a professional Disney Dance Mock Audition. In the audition, the dancers had to fill out paperwork, learn two short high-energy routines, and go through a cut process. The Disney experience was thrilling and inspirational for our team. Thank you to Spartan Elite Dance Company for joining us on our trip and helping make this trip possible. We had so much fun dancing with you! The Cougars are coached by Fine Arts Teacher Kaitlyn Quintana. Visit their webpage at www.cguhsd.org/cgCGUHSEliteDanceCo.aspx.

The team took a Masterclass where they learned professional Disney Parade choreography. CGEDC also had the opportunity to experience a professional Disney Dance Mock Audition. In the audition, the dancers had to fill out paperwork, learn two short high-energy routines, and go through a cut process. The Disney experience was thrilling and inspirational for our team. Thank you to Spartan Elite Dance Company for joining us on our trip and helping make this trip possible. We had so much fun dancing with you! The Cougars are coached by Fine Arts Teacher Kaitlyn Quintana. Visit their webpage at www.cguhsd.org/cgCGUHSEliteDanceCo.aspx.

post_text: The Spartan Elite Dance Company completed a Disney trip together this past weekend. They took two classes in Disneyland. One was a parade class, and the other was an audition class. This was the process of auditioning for Disney. It was a great experience. The Spartans are coached by Fine Arts Teacher Candralina Sanchez. post_text: STEM Engineering senior Madison Confer provided the first of a three-part training on quality management systems to the members of the CGUHS Robotics Team. Madison, who is a 4th year member of the team, took on the challenge this year of developing and implementing a formal quality program. She has been busy the past few weeks researching and creating a Quality Management Plan, writing a Quality Manual, and implementing a Quality Control Plan for the building of this year’s competition robot. Madison is being mentored by Troy Rosenow, Director of North America Quality for Abbott Industries and Sharon Bottock, Quality Director at Abbott Nutrition in Casa Grande. The Robotics Team is advised by CTE & Mathematics Teacher John Morris. Visit their webpage at www.cguhsd.org/cgRoboticsTeam.aspx.

post_text: The month of January was Charcoal Month in VGHS Art classes. The students learned several techniques using different types of charcoal. They had specific assignments throughout the month. During the week of January 27, they chose their own subject. This was their chance to show off the skills they had acquired and to put all the techniques learned to use. They took on the challenge and came up with amazing illustrations that were hand drawn, freehand, without tracing, and using nothing but charcoal. The Spartans are taught by Fine Arts & CTE Teacher Carlos Jimenez.

post_text: Mr. Rod Wood is a long-time Park Superintendent at the City of Casa Grande. He manages almost 20 parks in the city by visiting each site and going over what it needs in repairs, construction, and landscaping, and even solving issues such as vandalism. As the AzHOSA speaker on Tuesday, January 28, he was able to give a very good picture of his daily tasks including a short description of the parks we have in Casa Grande. Many of the students asked interesting questions such as what qualifications were required to be a Park Manager, his years of experience, and even legalities on where to plant trees. AzHOSA is advised by CTE & Science Teacher Noel Que.

The entire device, except for the electric motors and the battery, can be 3D printed in the Engineering classroom. The Cougars are taught by CTE and Mathematics Teacher John Morris. post_text: Seven (7) VGHS Thespians competed at the Southern Arizona Festival of Theatre (SAFT) on Saturday, January 25. Students competed in the musical solo and musical duet categories. They achieved six (6) “Superior” and one (1) “Excellent” and qualified for Nationals. Attendees were Arthur Bautista, Jade Martinez, Xela Mae Mercado, Drake Salas, Aaliyas Thompson, Payton Toscano, and Aurora Yoder. Receiving perfect scores from one of their judges were Arthur Bautista, Jade Martinez, and Aaliyas Thompson. The Spartans are directed by CTE & Fine Arts Teacher KJ Harding.

post_text: The VGHS Student Council attended the Arizona Association of Student Councils (AASC) State Convention held Thursday-Saturday, January 23-25. The AASC State Convention is a three-day event in which AASC business occurs, as well as recognition of the amazing accomplishments of student councils, students, advisors, administrations, and so much more throughout the prior school year. It's also an opportunity for every student council across the state to represent, converse, and share amazing ideas to bring back to their schools. The Spartans were awarded Council of Distinction Honorable Mention.

post_text: On Tuesday, January 21, CGUHS STEM Programs were presented at three Casa Grande middle schools. Headed by J. Leija, President of STEM Advisory Council, Biotechnology and Engineering students were able to showcase their skills in robotics, programming, microscopy, microbiology, and others to a crowd of young students of Casa Grande, Cactus, and Villago middle schools. President Leija introduced the team and highlighted the ways the future high schoolers could benefit from undergoing the STEM program. The team representatives earnestly and excitedly talked about their works as STEM students by showing the middle schoolers actual outputs and letting them experience how it was being done. The Cougars are advised by CTE & Science Teacher Noel Que.

post_text: On Monday, January 20, members of Students for the Exploration and Development of Space (SEDS) worked on their Rocket X-1 and the launcher for four hours. Their goal is to design a multi-stage solid fuel rocket that will reach an altitude of 10,000 feet. As a part of this project, the students are working with CG Fire Marshall Michael Wobster to develop launch safety procedures. Also on their agenda is to approach the City of Casa Grande about creating Spaceport Casa Grande, a permanent rocket launch facility. For more information on SEDS, visit www.cguhsd.org/cgSEDS.aspx. The Cougars are advised by CTE & Mathematics Teacher John Morris.

post_text: On Thursday, January 16, students from the fall Computer Aided Design (CAD) class tested for the Certified SOLIDWORKS Associate (CSWA) professional certification. The CSWA exam is the starting point for many CAD high school or college students who are looking to prove to employers that they can walk into a job and be productive on day one. It is a practical test that covers 3D modeling, design concepts, and sustainable design over the course of three hours. The Cougars are taught by CTE & Mathematics Teacher John Morris.

post_text: Payton Toscano has been named Rotary Student of the Month. She is a student at Vista Grande High School and daughter of David Toscano and Kim Velazquez. Her activities and accomplishments include being a member of National Honor Society, Robotics, Thespians, SkillsUSA, “We the People” class, and participating in many plays and musicals both in high school and the community. Her proudest accomplishment was performing in the Monte Awards after being nominated for best actress for her role as “Sophie” in the musical, Mamma Mia. After graduation, she plans on attending Northern Arizona University where she will further her skills as a writer.

post_text: Benjamin McFann has been named Rotary Student of the Month. He is a student at Casa Grande Union High School and the son of Gregory and Lori McFann. His activities and accomplishments include being a member of Health Occupational Students of America (HOSA), Robotics, and Students for the Exploration & Development of Space (SEDS). As a member of the STEM program, Benjamin finished the Biotechnology pathway early and passed the BASE exam to be a certified Biotechnician assistant. He has also been the CTE Student of the Month, was awarded the AP Scholar with Honor award, and has maintained a 4.0+ GPA. His personal activities include drawing (for which he won a competition sponsored by Kiwanis his freshman year) and playing tennis. He hopes to attend the University of Minnesota, Twin Cities, and study Astrophysics. He wants to work with NASA or become a teacher.

post_text: The Casa Grande Elks Club Lodge #1957 recently awarded CGUHS senior Brady Stephens the $2000 Jack & Lou Seil Memorial Scholarship based upon his Most Valuable Student Application. The scholarship was made possible by generous contributions to the scholarship program from Jack’s son, Mark Seil. Ranging from $1,000 per year to $12,500 per year, Most Valuable Student scholarships are for students pursuing a four-year degree, on a full-time basis, in a U.S. college or university. The Elks National Foundation will award 500 four-year scholarships to the highest-rated applicants in the 2020 competition.

post_text: The CGUHS Robotics Team continues with their competition robot design and build. The team is continuing their planning process while designing their robot with computer-aided design tools learned in their STEM Engineering coursework. With advice from Sharron Bottock, the QA Director at Abbott Casa Grande, the team will be implementing a strict quality control plan. The team is assembling a practice robot with which to begin testing their code. The robot will be operated in autonomous robot control and be driver controlled in a teleoperated mode. The combination of teleoperated code and the practice robot will allow drivers to begin practice with the robot much sooner than waiting for the competition robot to be completed.

post_text: Students on the CGUHS Robotics Team are designing and building a robot using SolidWorks 3D Modeling Software. Students create their 3D model to ensure fit and function before ever cutting metal. The 3D model is then converted into part drawings that the students fabricate and assemble. The design team is led by CGUHS STEM Engineering Senior John Travis Daniel and Robotics Team coached by CTE and Mathematics Teacher John Morris. The Robotics Team will travel to Flagstaff in March to compete against 50 teams from across the southwest for a spot at the World Championship in Houston in April.

post_text: On Friday, January 3, CGUHS STEM Engineering seniors John Travis Daniel and Chloé Buchanan led workshops on 3D modeling with SolidWorks at the 2020 FIRST Robotics Competition Kick Off Workshops in Phoenix. The CGUHS FIRST Robotics Team #996 and Introduction to Computer Aided Design (CAD) class is coached and taught by CTE and Mathematics Teacher John Morris.

post_text: CGUHS STEM Engineering I students competed in the 7th Annual Great Cardboard Chariot Race. In this project, teams of three students were to design, construct, and race a cardboard chariot on a course set up inside the U of the school. A chariot is defined to be a two-wheeled horse-drawn vehicle. Each chariot must carry one student as the chariot “driver” and be pulled by two student “horses” as is commonly depicted. The chariots were constructed of only corrugated cardboard and wood glue. After the race, the students examined the remains of their chariots to determine the critical failure mode and subsequent failures due to tensile, compressive, sheer, and torsional forces. A written report on their failure mode analysis will be due at the end of the week. The Cougars are taught by CTE & Mathematics Teacher John Morris.

His career goals are to graduate from Arizona State University (ASU) with a major in Digital Culture with a focus in Art in order to become a freelance artist and independent game developer.

post_text: During the week of December 2-6, VGHS Art I students learned to use oil pastels. This is a very difficult medium to master. The elements of design that were the focus of this project were Color, Texture, Form, and Shape. Students were to create a landscape that included water, mountains, and trees. After one lesson, students were able to put it all together. The Spartans are taught by Carlos Jimenez.

post_text: Special thanks to CGUHS English Teacher Molly Hunt for organizing the Letters to Santa Drive sponsored by Macy's Believe Campaign. Macy's donated $1 for every letter to Santa delivered during the month of December. On Thursday, December 5, that donation jumped to $2 per letter. Casa Grande Union High School delivered 17,158 letters, amounting to $34,316 towards the Make-A-Wish Foundation. Way to go, Cougars!

post_text: As part of the “Every Student Access” initiative, the Casa Grande Union High School District, in partnership with Sprint for ConnectED, is pleased to announce the availability of wireless hotspots for student checkout to those students who lack internet access in the home. The goal of this program is to provide equitable access to the district’s online systems, and educational resources for students while not at school. The program is open to families with at least one student enrolled in a school within the Casa Grande Union High School District and with no household Internet access at the time of sign-up. Visit http://www.cguhsd.org/Hotspot.aspx
